snippet.title: SuperCoach teams analysis round 22
snippet.content:
Sam Burgess - Named despite aggravating a rib injury on the weekend. Nathan Brown - Cleared of concussion by Parramatta officials and is a certain starter. Billy Slater - Returns from concussion for the Storm. Jordan Rapana - Returns from suspension for the Raiders. LOSERS Cameron Munster - Misses out for the Storm due to an ankle injury. Andrew McCullough - Out for the season with ACL and MCL injuries. Shaun Lane - Played from the bench last week, although the Sea Eagles have reversed this change in today's team. Bulldogs v Eels
Thursday, 7:50pm, ANZ Stadium
Bulldogs: 1. Will Hopoate 2. Brett Morris 3. Josh Morris 4. Chase Stanley 5. Marcelo Montoya 6. Josh Reynolds 7. Matt Frawley 8. Aiden Tolman 9. Moses Mbye 10. James Graham 11. Josh Jackson 12. Adam Elliott 13. David Klemmer. Interchange: 14. Sam Kasiano 15. Raymond Faitala-Mariner 16. Danny Fualalo 17. Michael Lichaa 19. Francis Tualau 20. Kerrod Holland 21. Asipeli Fine 23. Brenko Lee Ins: Asipeli Fine, Brenko Lee, Brett Morris, Francis Tualau Outs: None Team analysis: Brett Morris (concussion) returns on the wing in place of Kerrod Holland. Sam Kasiano (sternum) has been named despite an injury on the weekend. SuperCoach analysis: Aiden Tolman is the only SuperCoach-relevant player in this team, rocking three and five game averages of 67 and 65.6, although he's hardly an elite keeper. Eels: 1. Bevan French 2. Semi Radradra 3. Michael Jennings 4. Brad Takairangi 5. Kirisome Auva'a 6. Corey Norman 7. Mitchell Moses 8. Sosaia Vave 9. Cameron King 10. Tim Mannah 11. Manu Ma'u 12. Tepai Moeroa 13. Nathan Brown. Interchange: 14. Daniel Alvaro 15. Kenny Edwards 16. Suaia Matagi 17. Peni Terepo 18. David Gower 19. Will Smith 20. Frank Pritchard 21. Josh Hoffman Ins: David Gower, Frank Pritchard, Josh Hoffman, Will Smith Outs: None Team analysis: No changes, with Nathan Brown (concussion) cleared. Frank Pritchard (foot) and Josh Hoffman (knee) have been included on the extended bench as they step up their returns from injury. SuperCoach analysis: Nathan Brown has averaged mid 70s in non-injury affected games since round four, but is still only owned by 20 per cent. You could do worse than throwing the straight C on Brown in the first game of the round. Semi Radradra is a VC option against the Bulldogs, who he averages 70 against. Dragons v Rabbitohs
Friday, 6:00pm, SCG
Dragons: 1. Matthew Dufty 2. Nene Macdonald 3. Josh Dugan 4. Timoteo Lafai 5. Jason Nightingale 6. Gareth Widdop 7. Josh McCrone 8. Leeson Ah Mau 9. Cameron McInnes 10. Paul Vaughan 11.Tyson Frizell 12. Joel Thompson 13. Jack de Belin. Interchange: 14. Tariq Sims 15. Jacob Host 16. Russell Packer 17. Kurt Mann 18. Hame Sele 19. Taane Milne 20. Jake Marketo 21. Luciano Leilua Ins: Hame Sele, Jake Marketo, Luciano Leilua, Taane Milne Outs: None Team analysis: No changes despite the loss to Newcastle last week. SuperCoach analysis: Gareth Widdop flopped as the most purchased and captained player last week, but could easily have notched a ton if things went his way. He's a VC option this week against the struggling Bunnies. Matt Dufty is the fourth most purchased player and clearly cheapie of the week for those still chasing cash. He backed up his brilliant 124 on debut with a handy 41 in a beaten side (almost entirely in base) and is projected to rise by a massive $105,000. Paul Vaughan is the second most purchased player. , despite a misleading season average of 65.4, Vaughan has averaged almost 72 in non-injury-affected games this year, which places him amongst the elite forwards in SuperCoach. Rabbitohs: 1. Alex Johnston 2. Bryson Goodwin 3. Hymel Hunt 4. Tyrell Fuimaono 5. Robert Jennings 6. Cody Walker 7. Adam Reynolds 8. Thomas Burgess 9. Damien Cook 10. Zane Musgrove 11. John Sutton 12. Angus Crichton 13. Sam Burgess. Interchange: 14. Robbie Farah 15. George Burgess 16. Kyle Turner 17. Cameron Murray 18. Anthony Cherrington 19. Jack Gosiewski 20.David Tyrrell 22. Campbell Graham Ins: Anthony Cherrington, Campbell Graham, Jack Gosiewski, Zane Musgrove Outs: None Team analysis: Zane Musgrove comes in at starting prop, with David Tyrrell relegated to reserves. SuperCoach analysis: SuperCoaches have a great POD opportunity with Sam Burgess, who is owned by almost 50 per cent of SuperCoaches. He is carrying a rib injury and may see reduced minutes, so a late swap out of the 17 is a genuine tactic this week. Cody Walker is the seventh most sold after averaging just 50 in the last five rounds. Angus Crichton blows me away every week, notching 71 last round at just over a point per minute, despite a stint in the sin bin. Cowboys v Storm
Friday, 7.50pm, 1300Smiles Stadium
Cowboys: 1. Lachlan Coote 2. Kyle Feldt 3. Justin O'Neill 4. Kane Linnett 5. Antonio Winterstein 6. Te Maire Martin 7. Michael Morgan 8. John Asiata 9. Jake Granville 10. Scott Bolton 11. Gavin Cooper (c) 12. Ethan Lowe 13. Jason Taumalolo. Interchange: 14. Ben Hampton 15. Coen Hess 16. Shaun Fensom 17. Corey Jensen 18. Braden Uele 19. Kalyn Ponga 20. Sam Hoare 21. Javid Bowen Ins: Javid Bowen, Kalyn Ponga, Sam Hoare, Shaun Fensom Outs: None Team analysis: Shaun Fensom (ribs) returns on the bench with Braden Uele dropping to the reserves. SuperCoach analysis: He was a 70-80 minute specialist at the start of the year, but Jason Taumalolo hasn't played over 61 mins in his last five games. He's still scoring well (five game average 71), but he isn't quite a captaincy option. Storm: 1. Billy Slater 2. Suliasi Vunivalu 3. Will Chambers 4. Curtis Scott 5. Josh Addo-Carr 6. Ryley Jacks 7. Cooper Cronk 8. Jesse Bromwich 9. Cameron Smith (c) 10. Tim Glasby 11. Felise Kaufusi 12. Joe Stimson 13. Dale Finucane. Interchange: 14. Nelson Asofa-Solomona 15. Kenny Bromwich 16. Jordan McLean 17. Slade Griffin 18. Nate Myles 19. Jahrome Hughes 20. Brodie Croft 21. Robbie Rochow Ins: Billy Slater, Brodie Croft, Nate Myles, Robbie Rochow, Ryley Jacks Outs: Cameron Munster (ankle) Team analysis: Cameron Munster (ankle) is replaced at five-eighth by Ryley Jacks. Billy Slater (concussion) returns at fullback for Jahrome Hughes. SuperCoach analysis: Cameron Smith is the most purchased player after notching a career best four try assists in 143 against the Sea Eagles. Smith has averaged almost 16 more points than any other hooker and is an obvious must. Curtis Scott is the eighth most sold player after making a very handy $188,000 (BE 81). However, given Scott's form, those short on trades have no need to worry about Scott as an auto emergency. The Storm say Cameron Munster (ankle) is expected to miss just one game.
NRL: Breanna Holden and Tom Sangster discuss the players you need to buy, hold and sell heading into round 22.
SuperCoach: Buy, Hold, Sell Knights v Warriors
Saturday, 3:00pm, McDonald Jones Stadium
Knights: 1. Nathan Ross 2. Ken Sio 3. Dane Gagai 4. Peter Mata'utia 5. Shaun Kenny-Dowall 6. Brock Lamb 7. Trent Hodkinson 8. Daniel Saifiti 9. Jamie Buhrer 10. Josh King 11. Sione Mata'utia 12. Joe Wardle 13. Mitchell Barnett. Interchange: 14. Danny Levi 15. Luke Yates 16. Lachlan Fitzgibbon 17. Jacob Saifiti 18. Jack Cogger 19. Sam Stone 20. Brendan Elliot 21. Chanel Mata'utia Ins: Brendan Elliot, Chanel Mata'utia, Jack Cogger, Sam Stone Outs: None Team analysis: No changes. SuperCoach analysis: Nothing doing SuperCoach-wise, but this looms as the game of the round against the Warriors. Warriors: 1. Roger Tuivasa-Sheck (c) 2. David Fusitua 3. Blake Ayshford 4. Solomone Kata 5. Ken Maumalo 6. Kieran Foran 7. Mason Lino 8. Jacob Lillyman 9. Issac Luke 10. Ben Matulino 11. Isaiah Papalii 12. Bunty Afoa 13. Simon Mannering. Interchange: 14. Ata Hingano 15. Sam Lisone 16. Ligi Sao 17. James Bell 20. Tevita Satae 21. Nathaniel Roache 22. Charnze Nicoll-Klokstad Ins: Charnze Nicoll-Klokstad, Isaiah Papalii, Jazz Tevaga, Nathaniel Roache, Tevita Satae Outs: Bodene Thompson (pectoral, season) Team analysis: Bodene Thompson (pectoral, season) is replaced in the starting back row by rookie Isaiah Papalii. SuperCoach analysis: Roger Tuivasa-Sheck, like most Warriors players, has hit the skids following the injury to Shaun Johnson. He has averaged 47 in the last three rounds and is the fifth most sold player, but surely he's worth a spot in the 17 this week against the worst defence in the competition. Early-season cheapie Isaiah Papalii has been named for his first game since round one and could create auto emergency dramas. Over 20 per cent of SuperCoaches have their fingers crossed Papalii isn't shifted to the middle, which would see Simon Mannering play edge. Titans v Broncos
Saturday, 5:30pm, Cbus Super Stadium
Titans: 1. Jarryd Hayne 2. Anthony Don 3. Dale Copley 4. John Olive 5. William Zillman 6. Kane Elgey 7. Ashley Taylor 8. Jarrod Wallace 9. Nathan Peats 10. Ryan James 11. Kevin Proctor 12. Joe Greenwood 13. Max King. Interchange: 14. Tyrone Roberts 15. Morgan Boyle 16. Leivaha Pulu 17. Agnatius Paasi 18. Nathaniel Peteru 19. Phillip Sami 20. Pat Politoni 21. Paterika Vaivai Ins: John Olive, Kevin Proctor, Pat Politoni, Paterika Vaivai, Phillip Sami Outs: Karl Lawton (shoulder, season) Team analysis: Jarryd Hayne returns to the fullback hot seat, with Tyrone Roberts moving to the bench and John Olive coming in at centre. Kevin Proctor (hamstring) returns in the back row, with Morgan Boyle moving to the bench and Karl Lawton (shoulder, season) out. SuperCoach analysis: Ryan James has played 72 mins in his last two games, well up on his season average of 62 minutes. He's worth including in 17s for the 12 per cent who own him. Broncos: 1. Darius Boyd 2. David Mead 3. James Roberts 4. Tautau Moga 5. Jordan Kahu 6. Anthony Milford 7. Kodi Nikorima 8. Korbin Sims 9. Ben Hunt 10. Adam Blair 11. Alex Glenn 12. Matt Gillett 13. Josh McGuire. Interchange: 14. Sam Thaiday 15. Tevita Pangai Junior 16. Joe Ofahengaue 17. Benji Marshall 18. Corey Oates 19. Tom Opacic 20. Herman Ese'ese 21. Jamayne Isaako Ins: Corey Oates, David Mead, Herman Ese'ese, Jamayne Isaako, Kodi Nikorima, Tom Opacic Outs: Andrew McCullough (knee, season), Jonus Pearson Team analysis: Andrew McCullough (knee, season) is replaced at hooker by Ben Hunt, with Kodi Nikorima coming in at halfback. David Mead replaces Jonus Pearson on the wing. Corey Oates (staph infection) has been included in the reserves. SuperCoach analysis: The loss of Andrew McCullough is massive for the Broncos. Matt Gillett is one of the PODs of the year, rocking a five-game average of 90.2 but owned by just 5.5 per cent. Sharks v Raiders
Saturday, 7:30pm, Southern Cross Group Stadium
Sharks: 1. Valentine Holmes 2. Sosaia Feki 3. Jack Bird 4. Ricky Leutele 5. Gerard Beale 6. Fa'amanu Brown 7. Chad Townsend 8. Andrew Fifita 9. James Segeyaro 10. Matt Prior 11. Luke Lewis 12. Wade Graham 13. Paul Gallen. Interchange: 14. Jayson Bukuya 15. Chris Heighington 16. Jeremy Latimore 17. Kurt Capewell 18. Adam Clydsdale 19. Joseph Paulo 20. Sam Tagtaese 21. Edrick Lee Ins: Edrick Lee, Jack Bird, Joseph Paulo, Sam Tagataese Outs: None Team analysis: Fa'amanu Brown (concussion) has been named but is in doubt following a serious head knock. Jack Bird (sternum) returns at centre, Luke Capewell moves to the bench and Adam Clydsdale drops out. SuperCoach analysis: The Sharks have an interesting decision at five-eighth if both Jack Bird (sternum) and Fa'amanu Brown (concussion) are ruled out, with Joseph Paulo, Wade Graham and Luke Lewis all contenders. Paul Gallen is set for a big one at home following a down week (for him) away from Southern Cross Group Stadium. Raiders: 1. Jack Wighton 2. Nick Cotric 3. Jarrod Croker 4. Joseph Leilua 5. Jordan Rapana 6. Blake Austin 7. Aidan Sezer 8. Junior Paulo 9. Josh Hodgson 10. Shannon Boyd 11. Josh Papalii 12. Elliot Whitehead 13. Luke Bateman. Interchange: 14. Kurt Baptiste 15. Clay Priest 16. Dave Taylor 17. Joseph Tapine 18. Michael Oldfield 19. Jeff Lima 20. Royce Hunt 21. Erin Clark Ins: Erin Clark, Jordan Rapana, Josh Papalii, Royce Hunt Outs: None Team analysis: Jordan Rapana and Josh Papalii return from suspension. Rapana replaces Michael Oldfield on the wing. Papalii's return sees Joseph Tapine move to the bench and Jeff Lima drop out. SuperCoach analysis: Jarrod Croker is in the midst of his worst SuperCoach season since 2013, which is a strange thing to say given he is averaging a very handy 56.2. He returned to form last week with 115 and is a serious POD for the run home at 11.1 per cent ownership and juicy price of $315,100. Jordan Rapana has averaged just 35 over the last three rounds but is a must for 17s this week, having scored four tries in his last three games against Cronulla. Josh Papalii is fresh following two weeks off, has averaged 71.5 for the season and is only owned by 15 per cent. POD. Sea Eagles v Roosters
Sunday, 2:00pm, Lottoland
Sea Eagles: 1. Tom Trbojevic 2. Matthew Wright 3. Dylan Walker 4. Brian Kelly 5. Akuila Uate 6. Blake Green 7. Daly Cherry-Evans 8. Brenton Lawrence 9. Apisai Koroisau 10. Martin Taupau 11. Frank Winterstein 12. Shaun Lane 13. Jake Trbojevic. Interchange: 14. Lewis Brown 15. Brad Parker 16. Darcy Lussick 17. Lloyd Perrett 18. Jarrad Kennedy 19. Cameron Cullen 20. Jonathan Wright 21. Kelepi Tanginoa Ins: Brad Parker, Jarrad Kennedy, Jonathan Wright, Kelepi Tanginoa, Lloyd Perrett Outs: Addin Fonua-Blake (suspension, round 23) Team analysis: Lloyd Perrett joins the interchange for Addin Fonua-Blake (suspension, round 23). The Sea Eagles have reversed their late change from last week, with Shaun Lane named to start in the back row and Lewis Brown dropping back to the bench. Brad Parker scores a bench spot in front of Cameron Cullen. SuperCoach analysis: The Sea Eagles have hit the skids in actual NRL - and this has been reflected in SuperCoach scores. The likes of Daly Cherry-Evans (two week average 26) and Martin Taupau (three and five-game average in mid-50s) are struggling for points - and it won't get any easier against the Roosters, who have the third best defence in the comp. Shaun Lane was benched last week, although the change has been reversed in this week's teams. Nonetheless, with Lewis Brown back in the side, Lane looms as an auto emergency nightmare in the run home and those with trades should cash him in at a $144,000 profit. He is the second most sold player. Roosters: 1. Connor Watson 2. Daniel Tupou 3. Latrell Mitchell 4. Joseph Manu 5. Blake Ferguson 6. Luke Keary 7. Mitchell Pearce 8. Jared Waerea-Hargreaves 9. Victor Radley 10. Dylan Napa 11. Ryan Matterson 12. Mitchell Aubusson 13. Isaac Liu. Interchange: 14. Zane Tetevano 15. Sio Siua Taukeiaho 16. Aidan Guerra 17. Mitchell Cornish 18. Kane Evans 19. Jake Friend 20. Chris Smith 21. Nat Butcher Ins: Chris Smith, Jake Friend, Kane Evans, Nat Butcher Outs: None Team analysis: Unchanged 17, but expect plenty of action on game day. Victor Radley has been named at hooker despite a reported broken hand. Jake Friend (broken hand) has been included in the reserves. Boyd Cordner (calf/knee) misses out again. SuperCoach analysis: Jake Friend is gunning to be a late inclusion, which would be a massive boost for the second-placed Roosters. Panthers v Tigers
Sunday, 4:00pm, Pepper Stadium
Panthers: 1. Dylan Edwards 2. Josh Mansour 3. Tyrone Peachey 4. Waqa Blake 5. Dallin Watene Zelezniak 6. Tyrone May 7. Nathan Cleary 8. James Tamou 9. Peter Wallace 10. Reagan Campbell-Gillard 11. Corey Harawira-Naera 12. Isaah Yeo 13. Moses Leota. Interchange: 14. Sione Katoa 15. Bryce Cartwright 16. Tim Browne 17. James Fisher-Harris 18. Matt Moylan 19. Dean Whare 20. Viliame Kikau 21. Sitaleki Akauola Ins: Dean Whare, Matt Moylan, Moses Leota, Sitaleki Akauola, Viliame Kikau Outs: Leilani Latu (broken jaw, season) Team analysis: Leilani Latu (broken jaw, season) is out, replaced by Moses Leota in the starting side. Matt Moylan (hamstring) and Dean Whare (broken jaw) could both return to the top grade after being named in the reserves. Whare made a strong comeback through NSW Cup last week. SuperCoach analysis: Dean Whare has popped up on the extended bench following a strong return in NSW Cup on the weekend, which is a blow for Tyrone Peachey owners. Bryce Cartwright (season average 31.4) and Josh Mansour (season average 44.1) will be very popular for round one 2018. Tigers: 1. James Tedesco 2. David Nofoaluma 3. Esan Marsters 4. Kevin Naiqama 5. Malaki Watene-Zelezniak 6. Tuimoala Lolohea 7. Luke Brooks 8. Aaron Woods 9. Matt McIlwrick 10. Tim Grant 11. Chris Lawrence 12. Elijah Taylor 13. Matthew Eisenhuth. Interchange: 14. Alex Twal 15. Sauaso Sue 16. Michael Chee-Kam 17. Jack Littlejohn 18. Josh Aloiai 19. JJ Felise 20. Joel Edwards 21. Ava Seumanufagai Ins: Ava Seumanufagai, JJ Felise, Joel Edwards, Josh Aloiai Outs: None Team analysis: No changes. SuperCoach analysis: I've been on the repeater saying James Tedesco has been the unluckiest man in SuperCoach this year - and here's proof: The NRL bunker has denied Tedesco tries a whopping nine times this season through obstructions, offsides, dropped balls and being held up over the line. Both Teddy and Aaron Woods appear determined to end their time at the Tigers on a high, with Tedesco the fourth most purchased player this week. Originally published as
